      {
        "paragraph_index": 1,
        "text": "## Results\n\n| Metric | Value |\n|--------|-------|\n| Total metals in SRD-46 | **230** |\n| Metals with < 5 VLM measurements | **91** |\n| Fraction of all metals | **91 / 230 ≈ 39.6%** |\n\nAbout **40%** of all metal entries in SRD-46 have fewer than 5 VLM (stability constant) measurements. The vast majority of these (roughly 60+) have **zero** measurements — these include noble gases, superheavy elements, and exotic or unstable oxidation states (e.g., Cr⁴⁺, Mn⁴⁺, Ir⁴⁺, Po, At⁺) that are either chemically inert or too short-lived for solution-phase equilibrium studies. The remaining metals in this group have just 1–4 measurements, often representing organometallic cations (e.g., Et₃Sn⁺, Ph₃Sn⁺, Me₂Au⁺) or uncommon actinide species (Np³⁺, UO₂⁺). This highlights the highly uneven distribution of thermodynamic data — the bulk of SRD-46's measurements are concentrated among a relatively small set of well-studied metals like Cu²⁺, Ni²⁺, Fe³⁺, and the common lanthanides.\n\n*Source: NIST SRD-46 (Critically Selected Stability Constants of Metal Complexes)*",
